questions.text:
Consider the following algorithm that checks if node \( i \) is adjacent to node \( j \) using an adjacency list representation:

```
is-adjacent(i, j){
    for each v ∈ adj[j]
        if v = i
            then return true
    return false;
}
```
In the worst-case scenario, what is the time complexity of this operation?

questions.explanation:
Kruskal's algorithm processes edges in increasing order of weight:
1. (E,H) [3]: Sets {E,H}
2. (B,F) [4]: Sets {E,H}, {B,F}
3. (E,G) [5]: Sets {E,G,H}, {B,F}
4. (E,D) [6]: Sets {D,E,G,H}, {B,F}
5. (D,F) [7]: Merges {D,E,G,H} and {B,F} -> {B,D,E,F,G,H}.
The remaining singleton sets are {S}, {A}, and {C}.
